I. How it works
---------------

The web client consists of two parts:

  index.html    Self-contained single-page application (HTML + CSS +
                JavaScript, no external dependencies).  The page makes
                all API calls to http://localhost:<port>/cdse/* using
                the browser's fetch API.

  proxy.py      Python 3 reverse proxy.  It serves index.html at the
                root URL (/) and strips the /cdse prefix before
                forwarding every other request to the actual CDSE HTTPS
                server.

Browsers block direct cross-origin requests to the CDSE HTTPS server
(Same-Origin Policy).  proxy.py resolves this by making both the page and
the API appear to come from the same origin.


II. Prerequisites
-----------------

  Python 3 (standard library only — no pip installs needed)
  A running CaumeDSE instance (HTTPS on port 8443 by default, or
  HTTP on port 8080 for BYPASSTLSAUTHINHTTP builds)


III. Starting the proxy
-----------------------

From the a-web directory:

  # Against the default HTTPS server (self-signed cert)
  python3 proxy.py --insecure

  # Against the HTTP port (BYPASSTLSAUTHINHTTP build, no TLS)
  python3 proxy.py --insecure --cdse-server http://localhost:8080

  # Using a specific local port (default is 8080, which conflicts with
  # the CDSE HTTP port — use 8088 or another free port when both run together)
  python3 proxy.py --insecure --port 8088

  # Verify the server certificate with the development CA
  python3 proxy.py --cdse-server localhost:8443 \
      # (requires configuring ssl_context in proxy.py with the CA cert)

After starting you should see:

  CaumeDSE proxy running.
    Open: http://localhost:8080/
    Forwarding /cdse/* -> https://localhost:8443/*
  Press Ctrl+C to stop.

Then open the displayed URL in a browser.


IV. Using the web UI
--------------------

Connection panel (top of page)
  Enter the userId, orgId, orgKey, and storage name before making any
  request.  For the included development installation these are:

    userId  : EngineAdmin
    orgId   : EngineOrg
    orgKey  : 187465950C5F9018D04F91E976CAC1D7FA19CBA5FE26D94038630B18BCBAAAB6
    storage : EngineStorage

  The orgKey field is a password input — its value is not shown in the
  browser's developer tools request log as a plaintext string, though it
  is transmitted as a URL query parameter to the proxy.  Use this client
  on trusted networks only.

  Click the connection panel header to collapse or expand it once
  credentials are entered.

Tabs
  The page is divided into four tabs:

    Secrets    — raw-file secrets management
    Database   — encrypted CSV database management
    Audit Log  — engine transaction log
    Info       — user and organisation metadata


V. UI section reference
-----------------------

Secrets tab

  Upload Secret
    Secret name : identifier under which the file will be stored
    File        : local file to upload and encrypt
    Description : optional free-text metadata (resourceInfo)
    [Upload Secret] button

  Get / Download Secret
    Secret name : identifier to retrieve
    [Get Secret]      — retrieves and displays text content in the
                        results area
    [Download Secret] — downloads the decrypted content as a file named
                        after the secret

  Delete Secret
    Secret name : identifier to delete
    [Delete Secret] button

  List Secrets
    [List Secrets] — lists all stored secret names (result area below)

  Results area — shows the raw API response for the last action.

Database tab

  Create Database
    Database name  : document identifier (e.g. contacts)
    Column headers : comma-separated column names (e.g. id,name,email)
    [Create Database] button

  Insert Row
    Database name  : target document
    Values         : one col=val pair per line, e.g.
                       id=1
                       name=Alice
                       email=alice@example.com
    [Insert Row] button

  Query Database
    Database name  : target document
    Row number     : optional; leave blank to retrieve all rows
    [Query] button

  Update Row
    Database name  : target document
    Row number     : 1-based row index
    Values         : one col=val pair per line for columns to update
    [Update Row] button

  Delete Row
    Database name  : target document
    Row number     : 1-based row index
    [Delete Row] button

  Delete Database
    Database name  : document to delete entirely
    [Delete Database] button

  List Databases
    [List Databases] — lists all CSV documents

  Results area — shows the raw API response.

Audit Log tab
  [Load Audit Log] — fetches and displays the full transaction log.

Info tab
  [Get Info] — retrieves user/org information and displays it.


VI. Working with secrets
------------------------

1. Enter credentials in the Connection panel.

2. On the Secrets tab, select a local file (e.g. a key file or certificate)
   in the Upload section.  Enter a short name and an optional description,
   then click [Upload Secret].

   The results area shows a 200 OK response confirming the upload.

3. To retrieve the secret, enter its name in the Get section and click
   [Get Secret] to view text content, or [Download Secret] to save the
   decrypted file to disk.

4. To verify the list of stored secrets, click [List Secrets].

5. To remove a secret, enter its name in the Delete section and click
   [Delete Secret].

Example sequence (using the development credentials):
  Name:        my-tls-cert
  File:        /path/to/server.pem
  Description: TLS certificate for web server

  → Upload → List Secrets (confirm) → Download Secret (verify) → Delete


VII. Working with the encrypted database
-----------------------------------------

1. Create a database on the Database tab:
     Name:    employees
     Columns: id,name,department,salary

   Click [Create Database].

2. Insert rows one at a time using the Insert section.  Each col=val pair
   goes on its own line:
     Database: employees
     Values:
       id=1
       name=Alice
       department=Engineering
       salary=90000

   Click [Insert Row].  Repeat for additional rows.

3. Query all rows: enter the database name, leave Row number blank, click
   [Query].

   Expected output (CSV):
     id,name,department,salary
     1,Alice,Engineering,90000
     2,Bob,Marketing,75000

4. Query a single row: enter the database name and a row number, click
   [Query].

5. Update a row: enter the database name, row number, and the col=val pairs
   to change, click [Update Row].
     Row:    1
     Values:
       salary=95000

6. Delete a row: enter the database name and row number, click [Delete Row].

7. Delete the entire database: enter the name in the Delete Database
   section and click [Delete Database].


VIII. Viewing the audit log and user info
------------------------------------------

Audit Log tab
  Click [Load Audit Log] to retrieve the full transaction log.  Each row
  in the CSV output represents one API request with its timestamp, method,
  URL, response code, and authentication status.

  Note: the CDSE engine stores all field values encrypted.  The audit-log
  endpoint decrypts them using the orgKey before returning the CSV, so you
  must supply valid credentials to see human-readable entries.

Info tab
  Click [Get Info] to retrieve the authenticated user's metadata, including
  the userId, orgId, role, and storage resource name.


IX. TLS notes
--------------

  * If CDSE uses a self-signed certificate, start proxy.py with --insecure.
    This disables certificate verification only between proxy.py and CDSE;
    the browser connects to the proxy over plain HTTP.

  * Alternatively, visit https://localhost:8443 once in the browser and
    accept the security exception.  Then start proxy.py without --insecure
    so the proxy verifies the certificate.

  * For the BYPASSTLSAUTHINHTTP build, point the proxy at the HTTP port to
    avoid any TLS configuration entirely:

      python3 proxy.py --insecure --cdse-server http://localhost:8080

  * Never use --insecure or the HTTP port in production.


X. Proxy command reference
---------------------------

Usage:
  python3 proxy.py [--port PORT] [--cdse-server HOST:PORT] [--insecure]

Options:

  --port PORT            Local port to listen on.
                         Default: 8080.
                         Use a different port (e.g. 8088) when the CDSE
                         HTTP server is also using 8080.

  --cdse-server HOST     Target CDSE server.  May include a scheme
                         (http:// or https://).
                         Default: localhost:8443
                         Examples:
                           localhost:8443
                           https://cdse.internal:8443
                           http://localhost:8080

  --insecure             Disable TLS certificate verification when
                         forwarding to the CDSE HTTPS server.
                         Development use only.

URL routing:

  GET /             Serves index.html from the same directory as proxy.py.
  GET /index.html   Same as above.
  * /cdse/*         Strips /cdse prefix and forwards to the CDSE server.
  * Other paths     Returns 404.

Example — automated test:

  # Start proxy on port 8088 so it does not conflict with CDSE HTTP (8080)
  python3 proxy.py --insecure --cdse-server http://localhost:8080 --port 8088 &

  # Check index.html is served
  curl -s http://localhost:8088/ | grep -i caume

  # Exercise an API call through the proxy
  curl -s "http://localhost:8088/cdse/organizations/EngineOrg/users/EngineAdmin\
?userId=EngineAdmin&orgId=EngineOrg&orgKey=$CDSE_ORG_KEY"

  kill %1   # stop the proxy
